comments.body:
Instead of overloads, what about a conditional type?

```ts
nullable(isNullable?: boolean): MixedSchema<T extends true ? T | null : Exclude<T, null>>;

@DanielRosenwasser 	

Sweet, I like removing the overloads, makes the definition more readable.

However when I try this works fine but using a wrapper function becomes harder. The [wrapper test code here](https://github.com/DefinitelyTyped/DefinitelyTyped/pull/36155/files#diff-3ed4607a6b19a001ccf1d37f42e3f387R663) needs to be updated to the following. 

```TypeScrript
function wrapper<T>(b: false, msx: MixedSchema<T>): MixedSchema<T>;
function wrapper<T>(b: true, msx: MixedSchema<T>): MixedSchema<T | null>;

function wrapper<T>(b: boolean, msx: MixedSchema<T>): MixedSchema<T extends true ? T | null : Exclude<T, null>> {
    return msx.nullable(b);
}

const resultingSchema1 = wrapper<string | number>(false, yup.mixed().oneOf(['1', 2])); // $ExpectType MixedSchema<string | number>
const resultingSchema2 = wrapper<string | number>(true, yup.mixed().oneOf(['1', 2])); // $ExpectType MixedSchema<string | number | null>
```

So the overloads are still required else the resulting type changes and the return of the wrapper function is a lot more verbose.

Personally I would favor more complexity in the type definition with a simple API over a simple type definition and a more complex API for developers to use. 

Lets put this to the vote and see what the others think and go with that.

